Question 3

\[ \begin{aligned} F = (R_2^2 - R_1^2)/(k2 -K_1) \\ ----------------------- \\ (1-R_2^2)/(n-k-1)\\ \end{aligned} \]

Q1 SSE = 1319082976816.139

\[ \begin{aligned} R_1 ^2 = 1 - (SSE/SST)\\ R_1 ^2 = 1 - (1,319,082,976,816.139/12,694,825,780,588.189)\\ R_1^2 = 1 - (.103907)\\ R_1^2 = .896093 \end{aligned} \]

Q2 SSE = 576658649264.617

\[ \begin{aligned} R_2 ^2 = 1 - (SSE/SST)\\ R_2 ^2 = 1 - (576,658,649,264.617/12,694,825,780,588.189)\\ R_2^2 = 1 - (.0454247)\\ R_2^2 = .9545753 \end{aligned} \]

\[ \begin{aligned} F = (.9545753 - .896093)/(2 -1) \\ ----------------------- \\ (1-.9545753)/(1482-2-1)\\ F = 1904.152 \end{aligned} \]

result <- regress(
  DairyFarm,

Question 1 - Part B

  • Yes this model does suffer from multicollinearity as Vehicle_Class (39.901), Monthly_Premium_Auto (38.866), Coverage (7.726), and Total_Claim_Amount (5.242) all have VIF numbers greater than 5.
  • The log-liklihood of this model is -240.018.
